290","about 1309":"about 1309","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1334":"1334","Abt 1310":"about 1310","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","about 1295":"about 1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"England","Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England":"Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Semarc","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanized form of French <b>Saint Marc</b>, the name of a Huguenot family that migrated to the Palatinate.","English: variant of   Seymour  . This surname is very rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Seymour","meanings":["English (London): of Norman origin, a habitational name from Saint-Maur-des-Fossés (Seine), and possibly also from Saint-Maur-des-Bois (Manche) and Saint-Maur-sur-Loire (Touraine), named from the dedication of their churches to Saint Maur (see   Moore   3). The family of this name who have held the title Duke of Somerset since 1547 are said by some to have originated in Saint-Maur-des-Fossés (Seine), while others claim they are from Saint-Maur-sur-Loire (Touraine). They rose to prominence under the Tudors, when Edward Seymour (died 1552) held a high position of office under Henry VIII, who was married to Edward's sister, Jane. The Norman name has been established in Ireland since at least the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":20,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":33,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":42,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":87,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Elizabeth De Semarc was born about 1295, in England. She married John de Semarc about 1309, in Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1295–":"umbes 1295–Surnud","1290–1334":"1290–1334","1310–1349":"1310–1349","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","about 1309":"umbes 1309","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1334":"1334","Abt 1310":"umbes 1310","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","about 1295":"umbes 1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"England","Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England":"Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1295–":"noin 1295–Kuollut","1290–1334":"1290–1334","1310–1349":"1310–1349","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","about 1309":"noin 1309","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1334":"1334","Abt 1310":"noin 1310","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","about 1295":"noin 1295","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"England","Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England":"Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Nort